body:
I think rails should do what pg_dump does in this case: the constraint is emitted in a separate ALTER TABLE statement, like so:
```
CREATE TABLE public.invalid_test (
    a integer
);
ALTER TABLE public.invalid_test
    ADD CONSTRAINT invalid_test_a_check CHECK ((a > 0)) NOT VALID;
```
Then the NOT VALID flag is correctly understood.

I'm not sure that it's a good idea to have Postgres throw an ERROR when the NOT VALID flag is given at CREATE TABLE time; doing that would break scripts that work today.  Maybe raising a WARNING is sufficient to make users aware of the fact that NOT VALID is being ignored.
